<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-pop_mean-estimation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Estimating the population mean</title>
    <p>
        In practice, the true population mean is rarely known. Instead, we collect a sample
        from the population and use the information in that sample to estimate the unknown
        population mean. This process is known as <em>point estimation</em>, where a single
        value is used as the best estimate of a population parameter.
    </p>
    <p>
        The most natural estimate of the population mean is the sample mean. If a sample has
        an average value of <m>\bar{X}</m>, then the sample mean is used as the estimate of
        the population mean, denoted by <m>\hat{\mu}</m>. Although the true population mean
        remains unknown, the sample mean provides the best estimate based on the available
        data.
    </p>
    <p>
        It is important to distinguish between a <em>sample statistic</em> and a
        <em>population parameter</em>. A sample statistic is calculated directly from the
        observed data, whereas a population parameter describes the entire population and is
        usually unknown. An estimate uses the sample statistic to approximate the corresponding
        population parameter.
    </p>

    <table xml:id="table-estimation-mean-notation">
        <title>Notation for the sample mean and population mean.</title>
        <tabular halign="center">
            <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                <cell halign="left">Symbol</cell>
                <cell>Description</cell>
                <cell>Known?</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\bar{X}</m></cell>
                <cell>Sample mean</cell>
                <cell>Yes, calculated from the sample data.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\mu</m></cell>
                <cell>Population mean</cell>
                <cell>Usually unknown.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell halign="left"><m>\hat{\mu}</m></cell>
                <cell>Estimate of the population mean</cell>
                <cell>Yes, obtained using the sample mean.</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </table>

    <example xml:id="ex-estimating-population-mean-rinstat">
        <title>Estimating a population mean in R-Instat</title>
        <p>
            In this example, we use the <c>effort</c> dataset from the
            <c>lsrdata</c> package. The dataset contains 10 observations on two
            variables: <c>hours</c>, representing the number of study hours,
            and <c>grade</c>, representing the corresponding assessment grades.
        </p>
        <p>
            If the dataset has not already been loaded, import it by selecting
            <c>Import &gt; Import from Library...</c>. On the
            <c>Load from R</c> tab, choose <c>lsrdata</c> from the
            <c>From Package</c> drop-down list, then select the
            <c>effort</c> dataset and click <c>OK</c>.
        </p>
        <p>
            To calculate the sample means, open
            <c>Describe &gt; One Variable &gt; Summarise...</c>.
            On the <c>Default</c> tab, select both
            <c>hours</c> and <c>grade</c>, move them to the
            <c>Variable(s) to Summarise</c> box, and click
            <c>OK</c>.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-one-variable-summarise">
            <caption>
                The <c>One Variable Summarise</c> dialog with the
                <c>hours</c> and <c>grade</c> variables selected.
            </caption>
            <image source="images\estimation\one-variable-summarise.png"/>
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="fig-effort-summary-output">
            <caption>
                Summary statistics for the <c>effort</c> dataset.
            </caption>
            <image source="images\estimation\effort-summary-output.png"/>
        </figure>
        <p>
            The output shows that the sample mean for <c>hours</c> is
            <m>\bar{X}=36.8</m>, while the sample mean for
            <c>grade</c> is <m>\bar{X}=59.6</m>. These values are
            calculated directly from the sample and therefore are
            sample statistics.
        </p>
        <p>
            Assuming that the observations represent a simple random sample from
            a larger population, the sample means provide the point estimates of
            the corresponding population means. Therefore, the estimated population
            mean number of study hours is
            <m>\hat{\mu}_{hours}=36.8</m>, and the estimated population mean
            grade is <m>\hat{\mu}_{grade}=59.6</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            This example illustrates an important principle of statistical
            estimation: although the true population mean is unknown, the sample
            mean provides the best single-value estimate based on the observed
            data. In the next subsection, we explain why the sample mean is an
            appropriate estimator and discuss the desirable properties of good
            statistical estimators.
        </p>
    </example>
</subsection>